article.description: Seimone Augustus had 18 points and top-ranked LSU held Mississippi State scoreless for almost 14 minutes during the first half in a 67-40 victory.
article.headline: LSU wins eighth straight game
article.linkText: LSU holds Miss. State scoreless for 14 minutes
article.story:
STARKVILLE, Miss. (AP) -- The nation's leading scorer was no match for the Southeastern Conference's stingiest defense.

Top-ranked LSU held Mississippi State scoreless for almost 14 minutes during the first half in a 67-40 victory on Sunday. Mississippi State's Tan White, the nation's top scorer, finished with 20 points on 6-of-23 shooting.

White scored 47 points against Vanderbilt (No. 20 ESPN/USA Today, No. 21 AP) on Thursday in the most productive game by a Division I women's player this year. But it was no contest against LSU, who led 37-9 at halftime.

"To come in here and hold Mississippi State to nine in the first half, after the momentum they brought, was something nice to see," LSU coach Pokey Chatman said. "This particular (Tigers) team, when they lock in and not get in a hurry, they've been known to put together some pretty good offensive possessions."

Seimone Augustus, the SEC's second-leading scorer, had eight of her 18 points during a 35-3 stretch which broke the game open.

The Tigers (21-1, 8-0) scored the final 29 points of the half, shot 55 percent from the field and led 37-9 at halftime.

"As long as my team is executing and everything is going well, I feel that I'm going to have a great game -- the same game I always have as long as we're executing," said Augustus, who has scored at least 18 points in 15 games this season.

Freshman Sylvia Fowles added 12 points for LSU, which has won eight straight heading into Thursday's home game against No. 5 Tennessee, the only other team undefeated in SEC play.

"I'm blessed to have kids that are very good about perspective," Chatman said.

The Bulldogs (14-8, 3-6) couldn't get closer than 20 in the second half and have lost five straight and six of seven since starting the season 13-2.

Mississippi State showed little resemblance to the team that took Vanderbilt to double-overtime three days earlier. The Bulldogs shot 4-of-29 in the first half, missed their last 18 attempts and scored their final points on Ebonie Ferguson's 3-pointer with 13:57 until halftime.

"It's like a shark in the water when they see that blood," Mississippi State coach Sharon Fanning said. "I don't think the halftime score reflects how good they are or how bad we looked from those stats. I think we panicked."

The anticipated matchup of the conference's top two scorers never materialized.

White, who entered leading the nation in scoring with a 22.6-point average, said fatigue wasn't an issue after the quick turnaround from the double-overtime loss.

"I don't really think I lost anything," White said. "I just didn't come out as hot as I was the other night."

She was a non-factor in the first half with two points on 1-for-11 shooting.

LSU's defense entered leading the league in two key categories, allowing teams just 51.7 points and 34 percent shooting. The Tigers held Mississippi State to 26 percent shooting.

Temeka Johnson had four assists to set the SEC's career record with 820, breaking a tie with Camille Ratledge of Florida.

"My teammates do a great job of finishing for me as long as I get them the ball," Johnson said.

The Tigers have beaten Mississippi State 13 straight times and lead the series 34-4.
